All three, however, being actions proper, necessitated the attendance of both parties before the magistrate, and to secure th‘n was the business of the plaintiff. A summons srom the court or magistrate, which we now regard as the indispensable mode of commencing legal proceedings, was at Rome unheard of for many centuries. The first words of the Twelve Tables which have survived to us prescribed the mode of dealing with a defendant who refused to attend to his plaintid's summoue or ‘in ius vocatio ;’ the latter, after appealing to witnesses, could lay hande upon and take him by force before the praetor. The ‘Real' form of sacramentum is familiar to every reader of Sir Henry Maine's ‘Ancient Law.' It may be said to consist of three dramatic acts or stages, the first of which presente to us an oral pleading or altercation. The subject of dispute, eg. a slave-or if it be too large, a portion of it, is brought into court: whereupon the plaintiffi holding in one hand the festuca, or symbol ol absolute dominion, grasped it with the other, and touching it with the festuca said ‘hunc ego hominem (eg.) ex iure Quiritium meum esse aio secundum suam causam sicut dixi: ecce tibi vindictam imposui! This form was repeated hythe de fendant3 and both now grasping the object of their disputa we reach · the second act of the drama, a pretended trial by battle, symbolised in this simultaneous seizure or ‘manuum consertio! Lastly, to avert the simulated prospect of bloodshed, the state steps in ; the praetor, in the phrase ‘mittite ambo hominem: turns actual strife into peecefnl arbitration. The plaintiff now demands of the defendant the ground of his claim, and having heard it challenges him to lay a vager, the amount of which was fixed by the Twelve Tables, on its jusum a challenge which is repeated by his adversary.
